The §3Rock Breaker§r makes §6Lava§r and §6Water§r related products, such as §6Cobblestone§r, §6Granite§r and §6Obsidian§r.

In order to set this up, §eLava§r and §eWater§r must be placed §ahorizontally adjacent§r. §cThe fluids must not be in the front and back, they must be to the left and right!§r

Making §6Cobblestone§r this way is not a good idea, due to §bNuclearCraft §eCobblestone Generators§r, which don't cost any power. However, with §6HV §3Rock Breakers§r, you can make §eObsidian§r, without spending lots of §eLava§r!

§7LV§r and §bMV§r ones also exist, however, they aren't very useful.

§2Black Granite Processing is a great way to get tons of Fluorine and Thorium. Therefore, it is recommended to setup this process as soon as possible.

§6Fluorine§r is needed to produce §6Polytetrafluoroethylene§r (PTFE) and to process §6Naquadah§r, and §6Thorium§r is used to breed other elements in a §3Fission Reactor§r.

§3Rock Breakers§r are first used to achieve renewable §6Black Granite§r. This recipe runs at §dEV§r or higher, and can be performed without any water or lava present if done in a §3Processing Array§r.

After this, §3Macerators§r should pulverise the §6Black Granite§r into §6Black Granite Dust§r and a chance of §6Thorium§r. It is recommended to overclock this recipe as much as you can, in order to maximize output of §6Thorium§r.

A §3Centrifuge§r then turns §6Black Granite Dust§r into §6Biotite Dust§r and §6Silicon Dioxide Dust§r. The latter can be electrolysed, yielding §6Silicon§r and §6Oxygen§r.

§6Biotite Dust§r is then finally put into a §3Electrolyzer§r. This yields §6Potassium, Magnesium, Aluminium§r and §6Silicon Dust§r, as well as some §6Fluorine§r.

If you §osomehow§r run out of charge on your prospector. Simply submit it back in, and we'll give you a fresh one!

Available once per hour.

§oNote: this quest accepts the Wireless Terminal, Wireless Crafting Terminal, Wireless Pattern Terminal or Wireless Fluid Terminal.§r

Accessing §bApplied Energistics 2§r wirelessly saves a huge amount of time, and is highly recommended to set up.

First, you will need a §6Security Terminal§r, and a §6Wireless Access Point§r. Connect both to your network. Like the §6Terminal§r, the Wireless Access Point is a §emicropart§r, so you must place it on a §6ME Cable§r.

Next, you need a §6Wireless Terminal§r, or its variants. You can have as many Wireless Terminals or their variants on the system at the same time.

Finally, put your §6Wireless Terminal§r into the §6Security Terminal§r. This will connect it to the system.

You can equip these as a bauble, and use a hotkey to open them. Search 'Applied Energistics' as a §ecategory§r to see and edit these hotkeys.

You can only go 16 blocks away. However, you can put §6Wireless Boosters§r into the §6Wireless Access Point§r to increase the range. A better, but more expensive solution, that allows access from anywhere, will be explained in the following quest, 'AE2 Everywhere!'.

You also need to recharge your terminal manually. Although you can make this chore happen less often with a §6Flux Capacitor§r, wireless charging would be nice... Check out the §aWireless Charging Side Quest§r in §aMid Game§r!

Accessing AE2 from anywhere is a bit more expensive and complex, but its well worth it.

Firstly, you need to setup a §aQuantum Network Bridge§r. Build a 3 by 3 vertical ring with your §6Quantum Rings§r, leaving a hole in the middle. Finally, stick your §6Quantum Link Chamber§r in the hole, and connect it to your ME system. If you built it correctly, the textures of the rings should combine, leaving you with a §aMultiblock§r.

With your 2 Singularities, put it into an §3Inscriber§r or an §3Advanced Inscriber§r with a §6Advanced Card§r, resulting in a §6Quantum Link Card§r. Finally, put that into the §6Quantum Link Chamber§r of the §aQuantum Network Bridge§r, §cNOT the Wireless Terminal§r!

Now, simply connect your Quantum Ring to your AE2 network! Just remember that the multiblock §conly accepts connections on the edges§r, not on the corners, or the center block.

You should be good to go! You can now access AE2 anywhere, including in different dimensions!

If you are still manually charging your terminal... check out the §aWireless Charging Side Quest§r in §aMid Game§r!

The §aME Controller§r acts as the `brain' and a bit of power storage for an §eME Network§r.

Normally, this block acts as a source of §echannels§r, but those mechanics are disabled by default in §5Nomifactory§r.

You don't have to make this to operate a network when channels are disabled, but if you do, §eyour network will consume less power§r than if it did not have a Controller. Plus, they look kind of cool.

Make sure you craft the AE2 one though, and not the one from §bChisel§r!

Food for thought.

You're going to craft a §lLOT§r of stuff using §bDraconic Evolution Fusion§r. Therefore, a way to automate it is crucial.

Using §bPackagedDraconic§r, Draconic Fusion recipes can be easily automated through PackagedAuto. To get started, place a §6Fusion Package Crafter§r next to an §6Unpackager§r and surround it with §6Marked Fusion Crafting Injectors§r like a normal Fusion setup.

Note that Marked Fusion Crafting Injectors §cdo not§r accept §aME Power§r, only §eRF Power§r!

Now you can handle recipes through the Unpackager, just like any other PAuto setup! No more laser routing and messy conduit spaghetti!

§oNote: This quest accepts a Chisel of any type (Normal, Diamond or IChisel).

The §6Auto Chisel§r is a block added by... §bChisel§r, to automate all your chiseled block needs. Great for building big bases!

First, you need a §eChisel§r, and the Auto Chisel. All three chisels will act the same in the Auto Chisel.

Place the chisel in the Auto Chisel. If you are confused of where to place it, it's the slot with a Chisel ghost image, or at the middle-top of the GUI.

Right below the Chisel spot, in the middle-bottom of the GUI, place the block you
would like to chisel into.

You can also connect the Auto Chisel to power. This is optional, but will speed the process up by a lot.

Now you can simply access the Auto Chisel by means of item transport, like §6Item Conduits§r or §6Item Pipes§r.

Please note that you can only extract or insert items at the top or bottom of the Auto Chisel.

§2A brand new and highly requested mod to CEu to help you manage your tools!§r

The §eTool Belt§r is a item, which can store your tools, and exchange them easily! Right now, it has 2 slots, but later, once you unlock §6Steel§r, you can upgrade it with §6Belt Pouches§r, all the way to 9 slots, with an §3Anvil§r and some §aXP§r!

Make the Tool Belt, and you can use the keybind (default is §eR§r), while the belt is in your inventory or Bauble Slots §cand you are holding something, or the belt is not empty§r, to open its GUI.

Alternatively, you can right click while holding the belt to open its inventory.

The Tool Belt is equipable as a §bBauble§r. Open your inventory and look for the Baubles button, and click it to reveal the additional bauble slots menu, and then put it in the Belt Slot. Or, just click in every bauble slot until it goes in, if you can't tell which bauble slot looks like a belt.

The Tool Belt can store anything with a stack size of 1, like swords, pickaxes, §bGregTech§r tools, and the §6Terminal§r. It has also been modified a bit, so it also allows any §bStorage Drawers§r key, and §cdoesn't allow any Thermal Satchel§r.

Now, you can insert and extract from the belt! You can also use the Keybinds `§eCycle Tool Left§r' and `§eCycle Tool Right§r' whilst you are in the GUI.

A §6P2P Tunnel§r (§aPoint-to-Point Tunnel§r) is a powerful tool from §bApplied Energistics 2§r that can be used to send items, redstone, RF/EU or fluids from one location to another, using your ME system, without the need to use any disk storage space.

Each P2P tunnel system may have §aany number of inputs§r and §aany number of outputs§r. There is no limit on how many P2P tunnels, or P2P tunnel systems, you can have on one network.

By default, a P2P tunnel is an §6ME tunnel§r, which transmits Applied Energistics channels and power. Since channels are disabled, you will most likely not be using the default tunnel. You can change the mode of your P2P tunnels by using the assembler recipes or by §asneak-scrolling§r with the P2P tunnel in hand.

To configure your P2P tunnels, take a §6Memory Card§r. While holding the memory card, §ashift-right click§r the unconfigured tunnel, to set the frequency of the input, and save the frequency to the memory card. Once the first tunnel has been set up this way and the memory card is configured with the frequency, any subsequent tunnel you §aright-click§r with the memory card will be set as the output of the most recent frequency used. Alternatively, you can set a P2P tunnel as an §einput§r by §aright-clicking§r the tunnel with the §ecard in your off-hand§r.

You can also use memory cards to copy the configuration of ME blocks and tile-entities, such as §6Interfaces§r and §6Storage Buses§r. §aShift-right click§r a ME block to copy its configuration, and §aright-click§r to paste that configuration. Note that this doesn't copy upgrades applied to the block.

You can also §ashift-right click§r to empty the frequency, or the ME block configuration, set in the card.

Neeve, the master of Leveret. Summon him, and then bless him with your presents, and you shall gain access to his all-powerful rabbit.

All 3 tasks must be done to complete this secret quest!

This pack has §bInventory Bogo Sorter§r, allowing for quick, customizable, and easy sorting of any inventory.

The default sort keybind is §aMiddle Click§r, but you can always change the keybind. Simply hover over any slot in an inventory (§eChests§r, §eCrates§r, §ePlayer Inventory§r, etc.), click the sort keybind, and voila! A neat inventory.

You can also configure how your items are sorted within the Config GUI. The default key to open the GUI is §aK§r.

Inventory Bogo Sorter, by default, also §erefills stacks of items§r, like blocks, tools and food, from your inventory to your hotbar. For tools, it replaces it §ejust before it breaks§r, so you can repair it.

The §6Powered Spawner§r is a machine from §bEnderIO§r.

It is used to automate the spawning and capture of mobs. As with all §bEnderIO§r machines, it requires a capacitor, with a higher tier capacitor increasing the range, spawning rate, and capture rate.

In order to set a §6Powered Spawner§r to the mob type that you want, you must combine it with a §6Broken Spawner§r, set to your specified mob type, in an anvil.

This §6Broken Spawner§r is set by putting a §6Broken Spawner§r, of any mob type, and a §6Soul Vial§r, of the specified mob, into a §aSoul Binder§r, with a few dashes of §aXP§r. Broken Spawners can be obtained by breaking a mob spawner. §eTIP: Spawners are all over the Lost Cities!§r

The spawner has two modes: Capture and Spawn.

In capture mode, you insert a §6Soul Vial§r into the machine, and the soul vial captures the §asoul§r of the set mob. This does not spawn any mobs, and thus works with any mob, even on peaceful.

In spawn mode, the spawner will spawn the mob that it is set to, until there is no space for them, or there are too many mobs in the area.

Now you don't have to craft Soul Vials, but simply make them! It is also useful in certain crafts, such as the §aFlight Control Unit§r, in saving you a ton of XP.

A §6Programmed Circuit§r is an item used to configure machines. In essence, they tell a machine what to make if there's multiple things it could make from a certain input.

For example, the §3Wiremill§r produces different thicknesses of §6wires§r depending on the config - §ecircuit 1§r produces §61x wires§r, §ecircuit 4§r produces §64x wires§r, etc. The §eJEI§r recipe will tell you which circuit configuration is required.

Each machine and item input bus comes with a §2free "ghost circuit"§r. Click the circuit slot on the §dbottom right§r of the GUI to access this ghost circuit. Left- and right-click or scroll to adjust the configuration.

That said, the Programmed Circuit item (crafted from a single §6LV Circuit§r) still has its uses:

- Whilst holding a programmed circuit, shift-right click the machine to set a §bGhost Circuit§r of the same configuration in the machine's circuit slot.

- When you're sure that the items you put into a machine won't have any conflicts, you can put §emultiple circuit configs§r into a machine, and it will be able to handle recipes which call for any of those configs. This is useful for machines such as the §3Alloy Blast Smelter§r, but you won't encounter that for a while.

Handling §6Patterns§r gets tedious pretty quickly, from not having enough slots to move tens of them at a time, to having to multiply them when upgrading your §3Large Machines§r, which, when equipped with §3Parallel Control Hatches§r, may require you to supply more than one item at a time to utilize them to their fullest.

You don't want to supply one ingot and get two wires when your §3Large Wire Factory§r can take §e64 ingots§r and make §e128 wires§r at a time, right?

That's where the the §6Pattern Multi-Tool§r comes into play. Granted, multiplying patterns early on is not something that you need right away, but there's more to this little thing.

The base functionality it provides is its UI, which makes it possible to §emove, multiply, divide and clear patterns in bulk§r. When an §3ME Interface§r is right-clicked, the multi-tool directly interfaces with it as well.

Much like the §eNetwork Tool§r, the multi-tool is capable of adding its own UI to all relevant §3Terminals§r where patterns can be utilized, most notably §3ME Interface Terminals§r, allowing you to adjust your patterns on the fly.

As a bonus, it can also hold §6Blank Patterns§r, injecting them into your §3Pattern Terminals§r may you ever run out of them. Fill this thing with blanks!

Did you know that you now have the ability to build §3multi-block machines§r automatically? If you weren't aware, you're in for a surprise!

To get started, navigate to your §6Terminal§r, select §eApp Store§r, and scroll down until you locate §eMultiblock Helper§r. Inside, you'll discover an upgrade point titled §e"3D Builder"§r that's waiting for your attention. You can activate this upgrade by submitting §6two Workstations§r and §6four HV Emitters§r.

Once activated, sneak-right click on any multi-block controller with the Terminal in your hand to establish a connection. From the main screen, enter the Multiblock Helper app and you'll find that the 3D Builder §ehas now been unlocked§r.

A couple of features to highlight are the §e"Debug" button§r and the §e"Build block" button§r. The Debug feature allows you to verify the structural integrity of your build and provides a visual feedback if any adjustments are needed. On the other hand, the "Build block" button allows you to build specific blocks in the UI. Simply select the corresponding block from your inventory to place, then click the button.

After familiarizing yourself with these features, click on §e"Automatic Build"§r and watch as your Terminal takes blocks from your inventory and places them in the correct spots.

Be aware, however, that §ethe placements might not always match your expectations§r, especially when using §3Buses§r and §3Hatches§r. As a precaution, you might want to avoid having these in your inventory during the build process.

§2Research has returned to GregTech 1.12!§r The §3Assembly Line§r needs to be provided with §edata§r on how to craft items before it can craft them. Data on how to craft each item is stored in a §6Data Stick§r and read by a §aData Access Hatch§r. This data is required to craft §6LuV components§r, the §3Fusion Reactor§r, and some parts from §dDraconic Evolution§r.

To begin, craft a §3Scanner§r and a few §6Data Sticks§r. The initial Scanner recipes run at §6HV§r, but §1IV§r is required relatively soon so might as well make that one.

Press §bR§r on the item you want to craft in the and navigate to the §bScanner tab§r. This will tell you which item needs to be scanned to make the data for the new item. For example, §dLuV §6Electric Motors§r will require an §1IV §6Electric Motor§r to be scanned.

Place a §6Data Stick§r with the item to be scanned in the §3Scanner§r. The item will be §cconsumed§r and its data will be written to the §6Data Stick§r. Each §6Data item§r can only hold a §csingle recipe§r.

Finally, place the §6Data Stick§r into the §aData Access Hatch§r of your §3Assembly Line§r. It will now be able to craft that item.

Later, you will need more advanced §6Data Orbs§r and §6Data Modules§r to store data, and a §3Data Bank§r to read them.

If you need to create duplicate Data items, you can copy the data to a blank data item of the same type using the Scanner.

The §3Power Substation§r is GregTech's native mass power storage solution. At §cZPM§r tier and above, it can rival the §6Tier 7 Energy Core§r from Draconic Evolution.

The structure can accept up to 18 layers of 3x3 §aLapotronic Capacitor§r blocks. GT batteries can hold §d6x§r the EU their item counterparts can hold when crafted into a §aLapotronic Capacitor§r. The structure need not be made of all of the same tier blocks, but it must be full, so fill any empty space with §aEmpty Capacitor Blocks§r.

Insert power through §6Energy Hatches§r and extract from §6Dynamo Hatches§r, each of any tier. The Power Substation can accept special §664A Substation Hatches§r, as well as §aLaser Hatches§r.

The Power Substation will §cpassively lose 1%§r of its total capacity every 24 (real-life) hours, up to 100,000 EU/t per capacitor block. This is equivalent to §d5.8 billionths§r of its total capacity per tick, so this should not be a concern under regular operation.

§3World Accelerators§r accelerate the ticks of any non-§bGregTech§r machine adjacent to them. This is extremely handy especially in endgame, allows for immense speedup of §6Draconic Evolution Fusion Crafting, NuclearCraft Fission Reactors, Solar Panels, Resonators§r and more!

The §6HV§r WA accelerates by 8x, the §5EV§r WA accelerates by 16x, and the §1IV§r WA accelerates by 32x. They require an input of 6A of their voltage tier. Be sure to right-click the WA once with a §aScrewdriver§r to set it to §eTile Entity Mode§r, otherwise it will accelerate random ticks in a radius around it instead.

Make them in an §3Assembly Line§r with some very advanced components.

Combining an §aI/O Bus§r and an §aME Interface§r into a single block, these can be used in place of §aInput§r and §aOutput Buses/Hatches§r in GregTech multiblocks to connect them directly to your AE2 network.

Saves you that crucial block space, whilst giving you access to your usual features (such as §eGhost Circuits§r). They also have an extra storage space (for things like §6Lenses§r and §6Molds§r)!

Also, when you get tired of placing the same configuration over and over again, you can use §bGregTech §6Data Sticks§r to copy a ME Hatch/Bus Configuration!

In §9IV§r, you also unlock §6ME Stocking Input Buses and Hatches§r, which instead of storing a set amount of items/fluids itself, simply extracts items/fluids from the AE Network on demand. Technically, §einfinite throughput§r (or as much as your AE system can support), and saves having buffer items and fluids everywhere!

Note that only the Interface-textured side will connect to an ME network.
Unused Gap Quest. Prevents Overriding Of IDs.

The §3Data Bank§r acts as a mass storage for §6Data Sticks§r and §6Data Orbs§r. It is also required for reading §6Data Modules§r.

Connect an §3Optical Data Transmission Hatch§r on the Data Bank to an §3Optical Data Reception Hatch§r (replacing the §3Data Access Hatch§r) on your §3Assembly Line§r using §aOptical Cables§r, and it will be able to read the data of all data items within the Data Bank.

You can connect multiple §3Assembly Lines§r to a single Data Bank, but each one will need its own §3Transmission Hatch§r on the Data Bank.

§3Data Access Hatches§r and §3Optical Hatches§r can replace any of the §aComputer Casings§r in the structure, but it must have a minimum of §e3 §aComputer Casings§r. Each §3Data Access Hatch§r and §3Optical Hatch§r within the structure will consume §d1,920 EU/t§r regardless of their usage.

You will also need a §aMaintenance§r and §aEnergy Hatch§r, which can replace the §aHigh Power Casings§r in front.

Although this is not strictly required until you need to make and read §6Data Modules§r, your single §3Data Access Hatch§r on your §3Assembly Line§r will not have space to hold all the items you need to craft otherwise.

If your Assembly Line setups grow enough, you may need to §echain§r Data Banks. Connect the §3Transmission Hatch§r on the Data Bank with data to the §3Reception Hatch§r of a second Data Bank. The §ereceiving§r Data Bank will be able to read all the data within the transmitting Data Bank, and can send that data to more Assembly Lines or more Data Banks. However, this comes at a greatly increased energy cost for the transmitting Data Bank.

The §3Research Station§r is an advanced Scanner which consumes §dComputation Work§r provided by connected §3High Performance Computing Arrays§r to research §cZPM§r and higher items.

The function of this multiblock is similar to the Scanner. Place the §6Data Orb§r or §6Data Module§r into the §3Object Holder§r alongside the item to be scanned. After sufficient §dCWU§r has been drawn, the item will be §cconsumed§r and the corresponding data will be written to the data item. Ensure your §3HPCA§r is supplying sufficient §dCWU/t§r - check the scan recipe in §eJEI§r for how much is required.

§3Energy§r, §3Maintenance§r, and §3Computation Hatches§r can only replace the 9 §aComputer Casings§r between the §aComputer Heat Vents§r at the back of the structure. The §3Object Holder §cmust face§r the §3Research Station§r controller block.

The Research Station can be accelerated with excess §dCWU/t§r, but it §cdoes not overclock§r with extra §dEU/t§r. Initial recipes run on §dLuV§r power, but §cZPM§r will be required soon, and higher tiers of energy will be required for more advanced scans. As most Research scans take a long time, you should start this process early.

The §3High Performance Computing Array (HPCA)§r is a computer which provides §dComputation Work§r to be used in the §3Research Station§r. The amount of §dComputation Work§r it provides depends on the type of HPCA parts within it. It also needs to receive adequate §dCooling§r provided by Coolers within its structure.

Connect the §3Computation Data Transmission Hatch§r to the §3Reception Hatch§r on your §3Research Station§r to transfer the §dCWU/t§r produced to it.

The HPCA accepts almost any combination of §3Computation Components§r, §3Coolers§r, §3Bridges§r and §3Empty Components§r within the 3x3 area behind the §aComputer Heat Vents§r. The suggested components will build a §d16 CWU/t§r HPCA, enough for scanning the §3Fusion Reactor Mk2§r, §6UV Circuits§r, and all §6ZPM Components§r. You can get away with less at first, but you will eventually need to upgrade to this computing power. Refer to §eJEI§r for some other possible setups.

The §dCWU/t§r of the HPCA is determined by the sum of the outputs of the §3HPCA Computation Components§r within it. Regular §3Computation Components§r produce §d4 CWU/t§r each, and require §d2 Cooling§r each. §3Advanced Computation Components§r, which you do not have access to yet, produce §d16 CWU/t§r each and require §d4 Cooling§r each, and a fully upgraded HPCA can produce up to §d36 CWU/t§r.

§dCooling§r is provided by §3Cooler§r blocks within the structure. §3Passive Coolers§r provide §d1 Cooling§r each for free, whereas §3Active Coolers§r provide §d2 Cooling§r each with a steady flow of §9Dielectric PCB Coolant§r, provided through an §3Input Hatch§r. If the Cooling within the HPCA is insufficient, the components may be §cdamaged§r from overheating. The physical position of the components within the HPCA does not matter.

A §3Bridge Component§r may be installed, allowing the HPCA to connect to §3Network Switches§r.

The energy consumption of the HPCA is determined by the sum of its parts. 'Max Energy' refers to the power draw while the HPCA is computing, while 'Upkeep Energy' refers to the power draw when the HPCA is idling.

§2Optical Fiber Cables§r are used to transfer §eResearch Data§r between §3Data Banks§r and §3Assembly Lines§r, or §eComputation Data§r between §3High Performance Computation Arrays§r, §3Network Switches§r, and §3Research Stations§r.

Note that Optical connections are limited to one §aTransmission Hatch§r to one §aReception Hatch§r.

The §3Network Switch§r combines any number of §3Computation Data Reception Hatches§r into any number of §3Computation Data Transmission Hatches§r. This will be required when the §dCWU/t§r requirements of your §3Research Station§r exceed what a single §3HPCA§r can provide.

Connect the §3Computation Data Reception Hatches§r to your §3HPCAs§r with §3Bridge Components§r within them, and connect a single §3Computation Data Transmission Hatch§r to your §3Research Station§r, and it will receive the sum of §dCWU/t§r from all of your HPCAs!

Now, all §3Assembly Line§r recipes are available to you, given you have the §dCWU/t§r to research them. The most computationally demanding scan, for the §6Ultimate Battery§r, requires §d144 CWU/t§r.

The Network Switch consumes §d7,680 EU/t§r per §3Computation Hatch§r in its structure.

Once you scan and make your first §6UV Circuits§r and §6ZPM Field Generators§r, you can upgrade your §3HPCA Computing Components§r to §3Advanced Components§r. These produce §d16 CWU/t§r each and require §d4 Cooling§r each.

With them, you can upgrade a single HPCA to produce §d32 CWU/t§r total - enough for basic §6UV components§r, and the §3Network Switch§r, which will allow you to go higher.

The §3Chemical Bath§r is mainly used as an ore processing machine to extract byproducts from specific §6Crushed Ores§r with either §9Sodium Persulfate§r or §9Mercury§r. It can also dye items, as well as perform some specialised processes.

For now, you will need it to cool down §6Hot Kanthal Ingots§r and §6Hot Silicon Ingots§r with §9Water§r. §9Distilled Water§r can accelerate this process if you have it.

§6Silicon§r in its solid form is required to produce §6Transistors§r, which are required for §6HV Circuits§r. Notice that the recipe for a §6Hot Silicon Ingot§r calls for §d2,273 K§r. This is why we built §6Kanthal Coils§r earlier - §6Cupronickel Coils§r can't reach that temperature.

Directly heating §6Silicon Dust§r you get from Electrolyzing various materials is an option, but a slow and energy-hungry one. The better method is to obtain §6Silicon Dioxide Dust§r by repurposing the §6Glass§r you're producing for PPC, and heat it with §6Carbon Dust§r. This produces §6Silicon Ingots §dover 5x§r faster, with a side of §eCarbon Monoxide§r for use in various chemical processes.

Don't forget that what comes out of the §3EBF§r is a §6Hot Ingot§r - cool it in a §6Chemical Bath§r first before using. Later, you will build a §3Vacuum Freezer§r which can do it better.

The §3Active Transformer§r is a device which can convert any number and type of §dGT Energy Inputs§r into any number and type of §dGT Energy Outputs§r. That includes §664A Substation Hatches§r, as well as §aLaser Hatches§r - refer to the nearby quests for more details on those.

With §dRF Conduits§r and §3Energy Converters§r in this pack, this probably has limited use, but you can build it if you want.

The 8th tier of §6Solar Panel§r, this is required for making higher tier Solar Panels for the endgame. It's also a decent power source.

Note that when placed in a horizontal grid, §dsolars share power to each other§r. This means, to reduce lag, you can place a large grid, and have only several connections (the amount of solars per connection depends on the ratio of transfer limit to generation limit). For this solar, you can do only §a1 connection per 8 solars§r.

§eIn older versions, placing solars in large grids used to cause lag, but this is no longer the case.§r In fact, placing solars in a grid can sometimes even be §amore performant§r than using the old solar tower approach!

§aLasers§r are §dGregTech§r's native solution to high-volume power transfer. Each power tier starting at §1IV§r has §aLaser Hatches§r capable of transferring §d256A§r, §d1,024A§r and §d4,096A§r of their voltage's power!

Energy in the Laser Network flows from §aLaser Sources§r through §6Laser Transmitting Cables§r to §aLaser Targets§r. All these must be in a straight line - lasers don't bend, after all. Similarly to other power-related blocks, the tier of the §aLaser Target§r must not be lower than the tier of the §aLaser Source§r.

You can choose to use these when moving power between §3Active Transformers§r and your §3Power Substation§r.

Don't let the name deceive you. §6Small Storage Crates§r can be crafted with just wood and can hold 117 stacks of items in a single block.

These will be your storage solution until you get your §dME System§r up and running.

You can move them with the §6Storage Crate Keeper§r.

The §aAlarm§r is a simple tool which plays a loud sound when given a redstone signal. Useful for notifying you if things go wrong.

Right-click the block to configure its range and sound. This tool requires §d4 EU/t§r input to work.
The §6Reservoir Hatch§r acts as a truly infinite water source for multiblocks.

The §6Electric Prospector's Scanner§r given for free now has integration with §eJourneyMap§r.

Pick up surface rocks, right-click ore blocks, or use an electric prospector on ore mode to discover veins.

Press the "action key" (default: delete) while hovering over a vein to mark it as depleted (or not depleted).

Double-click a vein to mark it as a waypoint, and again to unmark it.

Most multiblocks now support §2rotation§r along any axis. Right-click with a wrench on a face with a rotation ↺ symbol to rotate the controller.

Multiblocks can also be §2reflected§r to form a mirror image of the normal structure. You don't need to do anything to the controller for this, a mirror image will automatically be recognized as a valid structure.

The rules for building multiblocks otherwise remain the same.

Take your setups to a new dimension!

The §3Cleanroom§r, §3Multiblock Miners/Drills§r, and §3Distillation Tower§r do not support being rotated.

§oThis quest accepts LV, MV or HV Miner.§r

The §3Miner§r mines ore blocks directly below it in a certain radius. Higher tier Miners operate faster and have larger covered areas.

The LV Miner calls for an §6LV Sensor§r, which requires a bit of §6Quartzite§r. Buy some if you haven't come across it yet. You also need to provide power there. Whether you setup some simple power production or carry it across in batteries is up to you.

At §5EV§r tier, you can build §3Drilling Plants§r instead.

§6Tungstensteel§r is an alloy of §6Tungsten§r and §6Steel.§r

This alloy is cooked in an §3Electric Blast Furnace§r and cooled in a §3Vacuum Freezer§r.

§6RF§r and §6EU P2P tunnels§r can be used to transport energy over your ME network. They connect §bmany inputs to many outputs§r, have §bno hard throughput limit§r and require §bno extra cables§r besides your existing ME network. They are often used to power machines in cleanrooms or other dimensions, but can also form your main power grid.

§6RF P2P§r requires a §c5% RF tax§r which is taken directly from your energy cells. The total RF P2P throughput rate of your network is therefore §climited by your energy storage§r, since you need to be able to store and provide enough energy to pay for all the tax in a tick at once. One §6Dense Energy Cell§r is enough to start with, but more will be needed eventually.

§6EU P2P§r also charges a §c5% EU tax§r, but deducts it from the throughput instead: No additional cells are necessary, but only 95% of the EU reaches the machine.

Be aware that EU P2P §cpreserves input voltage§r, so you need to be careful not to connect the wrong EU P2P channel to a machine.

In both cases §aEU is automatically converted to RF§r but not the other way around.

Energy P2P channels are linked just like other P2P tunnels, and a tunnel can be set to carry RF or EU by §aright-clicking§r it with an energy conduit/Gregtech cable or by §asneak-scrolling§r with any §6P2P tunnel§r in hand.

§bBetterP2P§r's §6Advanced Memory Card§r might be helpful in managing your energy P2P channels.

There are many §eCards§r in §bApplied Energistics 2§r and §bNeeve's AE2: Extended Life Additions§r, some of which are highlighted in this chapter. However, for the rest of them, it is up to you to discover them!

Simply search '@ae2 card' n §bJEI§r to find them, at which point you can simply see their tooltip for their usage!

Have fun exploring!

The fifth tier of component for AE §6Item Storage§r.

Used for a §a256k ME Storage Cell§r or a §a256k Crafting Storage§r.

The sixth tier of component for AE §6Item Storage§r.

Used for a §a1024k ME Storage Cell§r or a §a1024k Crafting Storage§r.

The penultimate tier of component for AE §6Item Storage§r.

Used for a §a4096k ME Storage Cell§r or a §a4096k Crafting Storage§r.

Almost there!

The ultimate tier of component for AE §6Item Storage§r.

Used for storing huge amounts of items or information, like in a §a16384k ME Storage Cell§r or a §a16384k Crafting Storage§r.

Almost infinite storage!
The fifth fluid storage component, used for §a256k Fluid Storage Cells§r.
The sixth fluid storage component, used for §a1024k Fluid Storage Cells§r.

The penultimate fluid storage component, used for §a4096k Fluid Storage Cells§r.

Almost there!

The ultimate fluid storage component, used for §a16384k Fluid Storage Cells§r.

Almost infinite storage!

Recipes dispatched by an §bME Interface§r with a §eJob Auto-Complete Card§r will complete without waiting for any specified outputs.

§d"Well that's kind of odd, why would I want that?"§r
Great question!

There's an old trick called the 'paper trick' where people would rename a paper in an anvil to create a unique item, set that as the output of a processing pattern, and cycle the paper out and back into the network after depositing the ingredients to trick §bAE2§r into 'completing' the craft.

§eThis card achieves the same thing but without item cycling.§r

This is frequently used for ordering an entire multiblock's components to dump into a chest for convenient building, which obviously doesn't have an output item as it's not a conventional craft.

Another common use is to send off §6Micro Miner§r missions for resources that are dumped into a processing pipeline (so you don't need to wait for it to actually finish). In this case it's also §asafer to use an auto-complete card§r, as you can inadvertently create §ccycles in the crafting tree§r if you're not careful. The Naquadah mission, for example, can end up depending on itself if the system is told the Miner mission outputs Naquadah dust.

Are you tired of making a whole new machine or adding a new input bus for each recipe with a different circuit? Well the §6Programmed Circuit Card§r has you covered!

Simply add one of these cards into a §aME Interface§r, and add the relevant §6Programmed Circuit§r to your recipe patterns. Now, when you order a recipe, the circuit will be set in the machine, on-demand! The recipe won't even require a circuit for crafting, thanks to §eGhost Circuits§r and the magic of these cards!

Also works with Multiblock §6Input Buses§r, and even works when there are §amultiple circuits in the pattern§r!

So much easier!

§aCrafting Cards§r are a useful tool for automation.

This card will generate crafting requests from the machine it is augmenting. In the case of an §aME Interface§r, crafting requests will be generated to keep the items in its stocking slots filled to the specified number.

Note that you can expose these stocked items back to the network with a §aStorage Bus§r, if you so wish.

Requests are made just like when you order them manually, except it will prioritize using the §osmallest§r available valid crafting computer.

For this reason you should consider adding a separate §31k Crafting Storage§r or §34k Crafting Storage§r as its own computer each time you use one of these cards, to prevent your main computers from being tied up with these crafting requests. If your craft doesn't fit into that, maybe reconsider using a crafting card for that item.

This card has been maligned for producing lag and performing poorly, which was definitely true in §bAE2§r back in 2020. §eHowever, these issues have long since been addressed in §bAE2-UEL§e, and are no longer a problem§r.

Want to make configuring your §6P2P Tunnels§r easier?

This pack has §bBetter(er) P2P§r, which adds the §6Advanced Memory Card§r. Using it, you can §aright-click§r on any ME device or cable that is attached to the current system. This will allow you to see all your current P2P connections without having to search for your tunnels.

To configure P2P tunnels, you need to select a P2P tunnel. This can be done in the GUI by clicking on its entry, or it can be done in-world by §aright-clicking§r on a P2P tunnel whilst holding the card.

Once a tunnel is selected, it will be highlighted in §agreen§r.

Connected outputs are highlighted in §6orange§r, and connected inputs are highlighted in §9blue§r.

An incorrect setup will show in §cred§r (Usually P2P device without input).

§aLeft-click§r on the name of the P2P to rename it.

§aRight-click§r on a P2P entry to change its type, or to change it from an input to an output (or vice versa).

The card has 5 modes accessible in the §3GUI§r, switchable via the second button to the left. These are:

§lBind to Output:§r
This mode sets the §aselected P2P§r as the §9input§r of the §bbind target§r (the entry you pressed §eBind§r on). Note that their input/output state and type are changed as necessary.

In this mode, the §bbind target§r can be any P2P on a different frequency than the §aselected P2P§r.

Note that the §aselected P2P§r becomes an §9input§r, and the §bbind target§r becomes an §aoutput§r.

§lBind to Input:§r
This is the same as §oBind to Output§r, except the §aselected P2P§r becomes an §6output§r, and the §bbind target§r becomes an §9input§r.

§lAdd as Input:§r
This simply adds the §aselected P2P§r as one of the §bbind target's §9inputs§r.

In this mode, the §bbind target§r must have the same type as the §aselected P2P§r, as well as on a different frequency.

Note that the §bbind target is not changed. The §aselected P2P§r becomes an §9input§r.

§lAdd as Output:§r
This is the same as §oAdd as Input§r, but the §aselected P2P§r becomes an §6output§r.

§lUnbind:§r
This mode simply allows you to unbind P2P entries. The §aselected P2P§r is not changed.

§6Interface P2P Tunnels§r are like an upgraded §6Item P2P Tunnel§r for §6ME Interfaces§r. These P2P Tunnels allow you to parallelize crafting patterns from a single ME Interface to many destinations.

The input tunnel should always be placed on an ME Interface, and the output tunnels on valid destinations for the §aEncoded Patterns§r contained in that ME Interface.

Unlike Item P2P Tunnels, which allow items sent through them to split across destinations, Interface P2P Tunnels §eensure that all of the items from a pattern end up at the same destination§r.

You can also §epush items back into the output tunnel§r and it will come out of the input tunnel, back into the adjacent ME Interface.

This also extends to having more than one input P2P, with output sides being able to pull from every input, allowing you to mass-pattern your machines.

Furthermore, the Interface P2P works with §6Fluid Interfaces§r as well, allowing you to push fluids back to a different input P2P adjacent to a Fluid Interface.

§eBlocking Mode§r also functions normally through Interface P2P Tunnels, only inserting items into a destination which is empty or equivalent (like config circuits).

If the above is confusing, think of it like this: §eeach destination is treated like it's actually adjacent to the ME Interface§r. Instead of at most five sides, you get as many "sides" of the interface as you want, with as many 'interfaces' as you want!

Laser-ify your ME Networks!

The §6ME Beam Former§r is a device that creates a beam between two points to connect networks over empty space or transparent blocks. You'll need two devices to set up a link.

This is great for transporting your ME Networks into §aCleanrooms§r, as an alternative to passing them through §6Machine Hulls§r, although they will have to pass through §6Cleanroom Glass§r and not §6Plascrete§r.

The beam updates in real-time based on changes to the blocks along its path. §eIf a non-transparent block gets in the way, the connection breaks§r. This makes it useful not only for linking networks together, but also for detecting arbitrary block updates if necessary.

The beam's color matches the cable color of the Beam Former it originates from. If the two devices have different cable colors, the color of the first activated Beam Former takes precedence.

The maximum distance the beam can cover is 32 blocks, or 34 blocks if you include the Beam Formers themselves.

Tired of the §3Atomic Reconstructor§r needing you to drop items on the ground and having to pick them back up again? Then you'll love the §6Reconstruction Chamber§r!

Push items into it and hit it with the Atomic Reconstructor's beam, and the items will be transformed as though they had been on the floor. Transformed items will be automatically ejected into an adjacent inventory (like an §aME Interface§r), allowing for convenient automation.

The Reconstruction Chamber is also compatible with comparators, so you can emit a redstone signal when it contains items. This means you can selectively enable the Atomic Reconstructor instead of relying on a pressure plate for a pulse, or constant-firing.

The §3Matter Condenser§r accepts large quantities of items or fluids to turn into data, which can ultimately be converted into a §6Singularity§r.

They can also make §6Matter Balls§r, but they are useless in this pack... well, except for being fired in the §eMatter Cannon§r, and being made into §6Paint Balls§r for the §eColor Applicator§r.

A storage component is needed for holding this data. Specifically, you need a §664k Storage Component§r to make a Singularity.

The fastest way to make these is with §aFluid Lasers§r and a §6Aqueous Accumulator§r.

Set the Aqueous Accumulator to output at a fluid laser, configure that fluid laser to `output', add a fluid laser on your matter condenser set to `input', and connect them together.

If you don't have that, you can surround it with §6Dense Cobblestone Generators§r.

Singularities are required for linking together §aQuantum Link Chambers§r, and for crafting different AE2 and NAE2 parts.

For the former, you want to detonate an explosive (like §eTiny TNT§r, §eTNT§r or §ePowderbarrel§r), with a §6Singularity§r and an §6Ender Pearl Dust§r dropped on the ground next to it.

This will create a pair of §6Quantum Entangled Singularities§r, which you can then place inside of a Quantum Link Chamber to connect them together.

The §aME Storage Exposer§r provides automation access to every item and fluid stored inside of your ME Network.

It's a lot like a §aController Slave§r from §bStorage Drawers§r: you can directly interact with this block using §6conduits§r, §6machine covers§r, or even other ME parts like §aStorage Buses§r or §aP2P§r.

§cThis functionality comes with a performance cost§r: the more things exposed by this block to automation, the more impact on TPS there will be. Use §efiltered subnets§r to expose just the relevant contents.

For example, you can create a subnet consisting of an §aOre Dictionary Storage Bus§r and an Exposer so that the exposer only sees very specific items from the main network. If you wanted to expose all ores from your network to this subnet, you could use §eore*§r in the Storage Bus's filter, and automation would have access to all your ores.

§aVoid Storage Cells§r can be placed anywhere a regular storage cell is allowed, but §call items or fluids that enter the cell are voided to create data for the §3Matter Condenser§r.

As such, you should §cbe extremely careful§r and partition the cell to filter which items or fluids are allowed to be voided using a §aCell Workbench§r.

One possible use case is putting them in an §3ME IO Port§r to mass-void junk items from your storage.

You might have experienced §5Advanced Rocketry§r before. Good news!

Going to the moon is §acompletely optional§r, but comes with some unique perks:

- §6Moon Dust§r, which can be centrifuged for the §9Deuterium§r you'll need to make your first §3Microverse Projector§r. It can also be used to make §6Quantum Flux§r more cheaply.

- §9Deuterium§r and §9Helium-3§r veins for your §3Fluid Rigs§r.

- Very high §aore density§r. §6Dilithium§r and §6Fluorite§r ores are only available from the Moon or microminer missions.

- Your rocket can be repurposed to set up a §3space station§r, which offers §apermanent daytime§r. Space bases are also just plain cool!

If this isn't enough to convince you, then §9Deuterium§r can be sourced by centrifuging or distilling §9Ender Air§r. An earlier but less efficient alternative is centrifuging §9Hydrogen§r,

Note that you will still need to make §9Rocket Fuel§r for your §6Tier 1-3 Microminers§r.
betterquesting:10.name:8: We Choose Not To Go To The Moon

betterquesting:10.desc:8: The §eMoon§r is full of, well, moon rocks. Macerate them to produce §6Moon Dust§r, which can be used as a source of §9Deuterium§r or to produce §6Quantum Flux§r more cheaply.

The §bGT Console§r is a very useful app for the §6Terminal§r that allows you to configure machines §awithout the use of tools§r. It also lets you set §aseparate sides for item and fluid auto-output§r, which is not possible using normal tools.

First, you'll need to install a §6Wireless Transmitter§r in the §bHardware Manager§r of your §6Terminal§r and add the §6GT Console§r app through the §bApp Store§r.

Then, right-click a machine with the §6Terminal§r while sneaking and click the §bGT Console§r app. This opens an interface where you can change the machine's settings, including the configuration of covers like conveyors and pumps.

Once you get used to it, this nifty little app will make setting up machines a lot easier!

the §6Void Satchel§r automatically voids any item going into its inventory. Useful for voiding excess §6Cobblestone§r or §6Netherrack§r when mining.

Can be §bconfigured§r with sneak-right click and set to §aauto-pickup items§r according to its filter by activating it (default key: §bV§r).

§cBe sure to configure the satchel correctly before turning on auto-pickup to avoid voiding valuables!§r

The main benefit of using §2Gregicality Multiblocks§r is their ability to parallelize.

It all starts with the §6Parallel Control Hatch§r, which is required for the machine to process multiple recipes at once. Higher-tier §6Parallel Hatches§r allow for more parallel processes. Additionally, you can open its GUI to configure the maximum number of parallels the multiblock is allowed to handle, but this is §enot particularly useful§r.

Parallel Mechanics work by essentially “downclocking” the recipe when it can, doubling its duration and quadrupling the number of parallels.

Let's see this in action with an example. In this case, we have a maximum of 4 parallels, an §9IV§r 4x energy hatch, and running an §bMV§r tier recipe. Since we have 4 amps of §9IV§r, we are effectively running at 1 amp of §dLuV§r.

1. The recipe gets overclocked normally. The voltage goes from §bMV§r to §dLuV§r, and the duration gets divided by §a16§r.

2. We apply the number of parallels. Since 4 amps of §9IV§r equal 1 amp of §dLuV§r, we can scale the voltage back to §9IV§r, and the multiply the overclocked duration by §a2§r.

There are some important things to note:

- §cThis is the MAXIMUM number of parallels!§r If there are not enough inputs, not enough output space, OR the voltage cannot be scaled down appropriately (e.g. trying to parallel 16x with 2A of IV in an IV recipe), the maximum may not always be reached.

- You need enough recipe inputs to run all the recipes, but you only need §bone of non-consumable items§r. For example, if you are laser engraving in parallel, you would need many chips, but only one lens.

- Chanced outputs are determined by the final tier the recipe runs at. For example, in the example, the chanced output would be the §9IV§r tier chance, not the §dLuV§r tier chance. This is one case where setting max parallels can be beneficial.

- The recipe may not always be scaled back! If the recipe has a §avery low EUt§r (usually in the ULV range), like §3Macerator§r recipes, the overclocked energy consumption may be low enough to grant parallels §dwithout increasing time or decreasing chanced outputs§r! For 2 EU/t recipes, you can actually parallelize §d16x§r without these consequences!

When setting up patterns for parallel machines, you may want your §apatterns in bulk§r. That is, if you have a machine with a maximum parallel of 16, you may want your patterns to contain enough inputs (and outputs) for 16 recipes, so you can use blocking mode, and have a high level of efficiency.

You can use the §6Pattern Multi-Tool§r to quickly multiply your existing patterns, and multiply patterns when you are upgrading your machines. You don't have to worry about having multiple circuits in your patterns; the §6Programmed Circuit Card§r will handle it perfectly.

With a §3Singularity§r, and a bit of setup, you can §amove your AE2 connection across dimensions and long distances.§r

To start, simply drop 1 §6Singularity§r and 1 §6Ender Dust§r and create an explosion nearby. This will create 2 §6Quantum Entangled Singularities§r. These are unique to any other entangled singularity you may create in the future, so it may be helpful to rename them.

Next, you need to setup a §aQuantum Network Bridge§r. Build a 3 by 3 vertical ring with your §6Quantum Rings§r, leaving a hole in the middle. Finally, stick your §6Quantum Link Chamber§r in the hole, and connect it to your ME system. If you built it correctly, the textures of the rings should combine, leaving you with a §aMultiblock§r.

Make 2 of these multiblocks: one at your base, and one at a remote location.

Put 1 §6Entangled Singularity§r into each network bridge.

There are several things you must do to ensure the connection works properly:

1. §aMake sure both sides are chunkloaded.§r

2. §eCheck your network connections!§r Quantum Bridges can only be connected by the edges. They cannot be connected through the corners or the middle block.

3. §cProvide both sides with power.§r You only need to provide an initial power boost to form the connection, then, if both sides are chunkloaded, both should draw power from the main network. It may be helpful to place a couple §3Energy Cells§r on the other side, just in case.

Now, you should be able to access your AE2 network in the new location!
Unused Gap Quest. Prevents Overriding Of IDs.

§3Centrifuges§r provide you with §21 tiny pile§r of additional materials when processing ore dusts (§e9 tiny piles = 1 dust§r). Sometimes it's the main dust, but often it's a different useful material that is otherwise unobtainable.

Instead of washing §6impure dusts§r (made from macerating or hammering ores) in a cauldron, you can get more out of each dust by centrifuging it. The same is true of §6pure dusts§r, when you eventually make a §3Washer§r or §3Chemical Bath§r. Note however that pure and impure dusts will usually give different byproducts (always check in §bJEI§r).

Lost an item? Don't worry! §5Nomi-CEu§r features §bFind My Items and Fluids!§r

This mod, as its name implies, allows you to search nearby inventories for §6Item§r and §9Fluids§r. Originally, you were able to do this with §bExtra Utilities 2§r, but it didn't support searching for fluids.

This mod features two hotkeys: §eY§r for searching items and §eT§r for searching fluids. To start, simply press §eY§r while hovering an item inside a GUI or even with §bJEI§r. Any inventories containing the specified item will §6Emit a particle effect§r.

While pressing §eT§r while hovering any fluid inside a GUI, any tanks or buckets containing the specified fluid will also emit a particle effect.

Note that the said mod only matches the type of item, not §eMetadata§r or §eNBT§r. For example, when you search with said mod using a §6GregTech Wrench§r, it will match any GregTech wrench made from any material.

§cKeep in mind nothing will happen if there are no fluids/items of that type nearby!§r

At some point, you will need to place down a §lLOT§r of §9simulation chambers§r, and doing the filtering for all of these can get annoying really quickly.

This is why we recommend using the §aUber Conduit Probe§r, a wonderful tool that allows you to copy the settings of a conduit, and apply them to a group of conduits.

First thing to do to use it is §6Shift+Scroll Wheel§r to select your mode (§agreen = copy§r, §dpurple = paste§r).

Once in §acopy mode§r, §6Right Click§r on the conduit you want to §acopy§r, and a message should appear in chat telling you it copied successfully.

Then, switch to §dpaste mode§r, a §cred area§r should appear, this is the area in which the uber probe will §dpaste§r the settings. Now simply select the §cred area§r to be the size you need it too, §6Right Click§r to confirm and §lDone§r
To exit the selection, simply §6Right Click§r in the air.

This electrifying coil gives permanent §dNight Vision§r when worn as a hat. Truly the height of fashion.

No side effects, no catch. Although you also need this for your §3Steam Dynamo§r...

§oThis quest accepts ULV or LV Conveyor Modules.§r

You will need to route a LOT of things through your machines in the future, so its worth setting up some basic automation to make handling §emass inputs§r easier.

For this, you will need §6Conveyors§r; the ULV ones are fairly cheap, although LV and higher ones offer higher transfer speeds.

You will also need two storage containers. At least one of them must be openable with a block on top, such as an §bActually Additions §6Storage Crate§r.

§aRight-click§r the target machine with a §eWrench§r to change the output side; set it to below the machine. In the machine GUI, enable auto-output in the bottom-left corner.

Now, place the conveyor, as a cover, on the top face of the machine. Use a §eScrewdriver§r to configure it to 'Import'.

Finally, place your storage containers, one directly below the machine, and one directly above. Simply place your inputs in the top container, and outputs will appear in the bottom!

If your machines process the inputs too fast, upgrade the conveyor!

You will be handling many different fluids, from §9Water§r and §9Steam§r to §9Lava§r. Some of these you might want to store, and others are collected from in-world.

For fluid collection, §bGregTech §6Cells§r is your best friend. Offering much more storage per item than a bucket, and being stackable, these allow for quick collection of in-world fluids, like Water and Lava. These come in many tiers, but currently, you can make §6Basic§r and §6Bronze§r cells.

You also have §6Universal Cells§r, made by simply placing a Basic Cell in a §3Crafting Table§r. These are the same as Basic Cells, but they can store partial buckets.

For fluid storage, you have many choices, but currently, you can only use §bEnderIO §6Portable Tanks§r, §bGregTech §6Drums§r or §bGregTech §6Wooden Barrels§r. Portable Tanks provide less storage, but are cheaper, and don't have restrictions on fluid temperature and type. Drums are available in multiple sizes, and allow for §aauto-output§r on the bottom side (use a §eScrewdriver§r to toggle).

§aNote the restrictions on fluid temperature and fluid type for Cells, Barrels and Drums!

§dNomi-CEu§r has another special feature: crafting recipes involving filled buckets can use §aany fluid container§r. Remember this when mass-crafting §6Water Sources§r or §6Cobblestone Generators§r. It can save you a lot of fiddling!

§aIn such recipes, only the fluid inside the container is consumed; not the container itself.§r

§oThis quest accepts a Nether Quartz Cutting Knife or a Certus Quartz Cutting Knife.§r

To prevent confusion, it may be useful to rename AE2 blocks or parts. Instead of spending XP in an §3Anvil§r, you can use a §aCutting Knife§r instead!

Simply right click any placed AE2 block or part, such as an §3Interface§r, §3P2P Tunnel§r, even a §3Terminal§r, and set a custom name! Right click the text box to clear it.

Your custom names will appear in your §bThe One Probe§r display, and even in some GUIs!

You don't want to keep sticking your §6Flux Capacitor§r into a charger? You want §eWireless Charging§r?

Well, you have two options: a §3Energetic Infuser§r with a §6Parabolic Flux Coupling§r augment, from §bThermal Expansion§r, or a §6Wireless Antenna§r from §bEnderIO§r.

§6Parabolic Flux Coupling§r charges §6Flux Capacitors§r in your inventory, up to §a32 blocks away§r from the infuser. It can charge your capacitors at 1/10th the max charge speed (e.g. 9k RF/t for reinforced, 16k RF/t for signalum, and 25k RF/t for resonant), but it can only charge one capacitor, per player, at a time.

§6Wireless Antenna§r charges any item in your inventory, up to §a24 blocks away§r. When you unlock §6Trinium Coils§r and §6Dark Soularium§r, you can upgrade this to a §6Enhanced Wireless Antenna§r, which has a range of 64 blocks, and even add §6Wireless Antenna Extensions§r to each side, increasing the range to a whopping 192 blocks. However, the transfer speed is limited to 10k RF/t per player.

§cNote that the Wireless Antenna only accepts energy from the bottom.§r

Pick your poison: more transfer speed, or more range? Of course, you could use both, but do you really need that much power?

You can visually place items using the §ePlace Item in World§r feature from §bDraconic Evolution§r. The default keybind for this is §aP§r. Picking back up items is as simple as §aright-clicking§r.

One application is to use this to label your machines, as a more visually distinct alternative to signs. You can also place items near where you want them (e.g. §6Molds§r), or just use this for decoration.

You are now going to need a supply of animal meat, to make §6Mincemeat§r. Since you need this in large amounts, and passively, you have two options:

1. Make a §3Fisher§r. This consumes §6String§r, and requires a 5x5 pool of water, with the fisher centered on top. You might need more than 1!

2. Setup an §6Animal Farm§r. This has the benefit of providing you with a supply of §6Leather§r (if you farm §eCows§r), and §6Experience§r.

To setup a farm, first, you will need a §6Broken Spawner§r, which you can obtain from breaking any §6Spawner§r. (Try the §aLost Cities§r!) You have to combine this in a §bSoul Binder§r with a §6Soul Vial§r set to the animal you wish to farm, and then you combine the resulting broken spawner with a §6Powered Spawner§r in an §bAnvil§r.

Now, you can place this spawner in an enclosed area. You can line the floor with §6Vector Plates§r to move the animals to a more concentrated location, and then simply give the spawner a capacitor and RF.

The easiest way to kill the animals is with §bExtra Utilities §6Gold or Diamond Spikes§r; you can then collect the items and experience with §bEnderIO§r's §eVacuum Chest§r and §eXP Vacuum§r.

You can also be more creative if you want... but this quest still needs those to be completed. If you setup a live exposed wire line with a constant power source and sink, so be it, but you still need those spikes.

As you begin expanding your automation sights, soon enough, you may come across a situation that requires you to passively craft something. In that case, you have three main options: §6Mechanical Crafters§r from §bExtra Utilities§r, §6Crafters§r from §bEnderIO§r, or §6Molecular Assemblers§r from §bApplied Energistics 2§r. Each have their pros and cons, so read carefully!

§6Mechanical Crafters§r require no power. None at all! Simply place it down, set the recipe, and pipe inputs and outputs. However, the speed is quite slow... and to upgrade it, you will need §eGrid Power§r.

§6Crafters§r (the ones from §bEnderIO§r) are setup in a similar way to their §bExtra Utilities§r counterpart, but they require power. However they are far easier to upgrade, simply requiring a better capacitor and more power. However, their top speed is not a match for the §6Mechanical Crafters§r' top speed.

Finally, §6Molecular Assemblers§r have a faster base speed, are fairly easy to upgrade, and have a good top speed. However, they take more setup, and are more expensive.

To setup a molecular assembler for passive crafting, you need to encode a pattern for that crafting recipe, place that in the assembler, §cNOT an Interface§r, and pipe in inputs. Note that the assembler can auto-output, even to other assemblers, allowing for you to chain outputs!

There are two main types of §3Fission Reactors§r: §aBreeder§r and §aPower§r reactors. A breeder reactor is a reactor optimized to generate §bfission products the fastest§r. A power reactor, on the other hand, is optimized to generate the §bmost power it can§r.

Whilst technically, power reactors are also very good at breeding, their design and maintenance is usually §emore involved§r. So, in fission reactions where you use power reactors, you do not need a breeder reactor for that reacion. §cBreeder Reactors generally produce very little power!§r

You will need at least one breeder reactor, but whether you pursue power generation is up to you. §eHowever, Fission Reactors are a good power source, and can greatly improve power stability!§r

A breeder reactor's only important factors are §ahow much reactor cells it has§r, and §astaying heat neutral/negative§r. A reactor with two times more reactor cells will generate two times more fission products as long as they are both heat neutral.

The most common design for a breeder reactor is the §9Cryolattice§r, explained in the following quests. While this is not the most efficient, as using §eActive Cooling§r can improve your efficiency, constantly consuming coolant may not be preferred, and breeder reactors do not need active coolers to produce products fast.

However, a power focused reactor has many more considerations, including considering the balance of §6Reactor Cells§r and §6Moderator Blocks§r, to improve §afuel efficiency§r, §astaying heat neutral/negative§r and §amaximize power generation§r. Because of the extra heat generated by moderator blocks, power reactors should pretty much always use active cooling, making them §cmore expensive to maintain§r. These extra considerations also mean there is no easy optimal design.

For power reactors in Nomi-CEu, you probably want to focus on using §eTBU Fuel§r, through §6Thorium§r obtained through processing §bBlack Granite§r.

You can also combine this with another reactor that uses §eLEU-233 Fuel§r. This is made with §6Uranium 233§r, obtained from §bTBU Recycling§r, and §6Uranium 238§r, from processing §bRed Granite§r.

LEU-233 can generate a lot more energy, but needs more supporting infrastructure. If you want to have a LEU-233 power reactor, you probably want to setup a TBU power reactor first, to build up your Uranium-233 supply.

To plan these, you will need an alternative rather than a guide... maybe a reactor planner, or a reactor generator? Check out the following quests.

Also, planning reactors and then pasting them can be faster than building them, even for breeders! Check out the following quests even if you aren't planning a power focused reactor.

§eNote: text like <{link}>https://github.com/Nomi-CEu/<|>this<{link}> are clickable links!§r

Since power reactors are so complex, you'll need a program to design them. Enter: §areactor generators and designers§r! (You can also design breeder reactors if you want)

Reactor generators allow you to simply use an algorithm to find an efficient reactor, using your chosen fuel. These can generate §cworse reactors§r than designing it yourself, but they save lots of time, and can provide a good foundational reactor.

In contrast, reactor designers allow you to design a reactor outside of the game, and see its fuel consumption, power production, heat, and more, allowing you to save hours of your time manually building reactors in-game. These can be used to §atweak generated reactors§r, or even §amanually designing a reactor from scratch§r, which can lead to very efficient reactors, fine tuned to your specific situation.

§eWhen designing power reactors, consider using Cryotheum Active Coolers as your coolers!§r Perhaps, even your ONLY coolers!

Nomi-CEu increases power generation from Fission Reactors to §a7x§r the base value. Please take this into mind when designing reactors. Fuel burn times, fuel heat productions, and cooler values are §cnot changed§r from the base values.

§cNote that Oxide Fuels are not available in Nomi-CEu!§r

For generating reactors, consider using <{link}>https://leu-235.com<|>LEU-235<{link}> (the program, not the fuel). This is a simple online reactor generator.

It allows you to specify the dimension of the reactor, what blocks to include, and what blocks not to. It is simple to use, pretty low effort, and allows you to generate working, decent reactors with a very little amount of time spent.

Designing reactors can be done through two main programs:

* <{link}>https://github.com/hellrage/NC-Reactor-Planner/releases<|>Hellrage's Nuclear Reactor Planner<{link}>: This is an easy to use yet functionally dense planner. §eMake sure you download the latest non-overhaul version! §cNote: it does not work on Mac, and doesn't function well on Linux.§r

* <{link}>https://balam314.github.io/Einsteinium/<|>Einsteinium<{link}>: This is also an easy to use planner, but has less features than Hellrage's planner. However, it has the advantage of being a web-based service, so no downloading and setting up, and it works on all OSes. §cHowever, it currently has issues with designing reactors bigger than 10x10x10.§r

But now you've designed the reactor, you don't want to build it manually, do you? Well, see the next quest then!

§oNote: This quest accepts any combination of Transparent and Opaque Fission Reactor Casings, as long as the amount of the casings combined is more than 150.§r

This quest teaches you to build a §6Cryolattice§r, a simple breeder reactor to get you all the §bNuclearCraft§r isotopes you need. This reactor is easily expandable by following the same pattern, to run faster.

This reactor is capable of running any Low-Enriched Fuel, such as TBU and LEU-235. This includes fuels made from other nuclear isotopes, as long as the fuel is of the low-enriched variety.

§eYou don't need a breeder reactor for every fission fuel! Your power reactors consume fuel quickly, so any fuels they consume don't need to be bred. You can also combine different fuels into one reactor!§r

First, set up your 150 §6Fission Reactor Casings§r to encase a 5x5x5 cube shape of empty air. Any of these reactor casings can be changed to §6Transparent Fission Reactor Casings§r. The Casings should cover only the faces of the interior cube, §cnot the edges or corners§r. You should have exactly the right number of Casings to encase a 5x5x5 space.

Next, create a hole so you can get inside the cube.

Place the §6Reactor Cells§r in an alternating pattern, with the reactor cells at the corners, and spaces between each one. Alternate between each row, creating a grid pattern. Fill in the §6Cryotheum Coolers§r between, in the empty holes. Do this for every layer, alternating between §6Cryotheum Coolers§r on the corners and §6Reactor Cells§r on the corners.

You should have the perfect amount of §6Reactor Cells§r and §6Cryotheum Coolers§r for this, and the third and final layers should be the same as the first one. The reactor will now be complete when you reseal it up with the Casings you removed to access the interior.

Finally, place the §3Fission Reactor Controller§r along any edge or corner of the reactor. Opening the Reactor Controller GUI should let you know that the structure was properly formed; if not, go back and check what you did wrong.

The lever is placed on the controller, as a redstone signal is required for it to start working.

§eNote: text like <{link}>https://github.com/Nomi-CEu/<|>this<{link}> are clickable links!§r

You can export your generated or designed reactors to a §eBG String§r, which allows you to paste them in-world through the §6Copy Paste Gadget§r.

First, export your reactor as §aa JSON file§r. In §eHellrage§r and §eEinsteinium§r, this button can be found on the sidebar ('§aSave Reactor§r' for Hellrage, '§aDownload Reactor as JSON§r' for Einsteinium). In §eLEU-235§r, this can be found next to the 'Stop' button (called '§aSave JSON§r').

Next, go to <{link}>https://nomi-ceu.github.io/NC-Formatter/<|>Nomi-CEu's NC-Formatter<{link}>, and upload your JSON. Check the data, select your desired options (pasting in §6Active Coolers§r and §6Casings§r can be very helpful!), and copy the exported string.

Now, place down a §3Template Manager§r, and enter the GUI. Place a §6Paper§r in the right slot. Now, press the §aPaste§r button, and the paper will turn into a §6Template§r!

Place your §6Copy Paste Gadget§r in the left slot, and click §aImport§r. Now, in 'paste mode', your gadget can place your newly designed reactor!

Remember to replace casings with §6Buffers§r where required, and place down a §6Fission Controller§r with a §6Lever§r to turn the reactor on.

Do you want to automate some §6Coffee§r into your hotbar when you finish drinking it? Or do you want to automate your own inventory? Well, have I got a solution for you: the §6Player Chest§r!

With this, you can configure which slots are accessible to automation, and then simply pipe items in or out.

For example, you can have a slot dedicated for coffee, where after you drink it, the cup gets extracted and a new coffee comes in, or even do more complex tasks involving your inventory.

Automation at its highest level!

With your §6Europium§r, you can now create a §cZPM §3Assembling Machine§r.

Now, you can make §6Trinium Coils§r, §6ZPM Energy Input Hatches§r and more!

GregTech §7Low Voltage§r Tier: start building a factory!

Unlock access to §bDeep Mob Evolution§r, early §bEnderIO§r tech, and §bApplied Energistics 2§r Digital Storage.

Build an §3Electric Blast Furnace§r for smelting advanced materials and alloys.

GregTech §bMedium Voltage§r Tier: new machines and rudimentary ore processing.

Chemistry for §6Plastics§r, and build a §3Distillation Tower§r.

§bApplied Energistics 2§r automation. Explore §bActually Additions§r.

GregTech §6High Voltage§r, §5Extreme Voltage§r, and §1Insane Voltage§r tiers:

§3Cryogenic Distillation§r, and petrochemistry for §6Epoxy§r and §2Cetane-Boosted Diesel§r.

Craft §6Nether Stars§r and unlock §bThermal Expansion§r machines.

Build a §bNuclearCraft§r fission reactor to obtain new materials.

Build a Space Station and Warp Core.

It's always rewarding to take a step forward.

This tab outlines the progression of various things in §5Nomifactory§r.

Circuits are the primary measure of your progress.

GregTech §dLuV§r, ZPM, §3UV§r, §4UHV§r tiers:

Build §3Assembly Lines§r, §3Fusion Reactors§r, and more!

Automate in style with §bPackagedAuto§r. Climb the tiers of §6Micro Miners§r.
